<header class="header">
  <h1>Day-Neutral vs June-Bearing Strawberries</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Choose a strawberry type based on harvest pattern, climate, and how you want to use the patch.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>June-bearing strawberries usually give one main crop, while day-neutral strawberries can produce smaller flushes over a longer part of the season.</strong>
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
  <p>
    Choose June-bearing strawberries if you want a concentrated harvest for fresh eating, freezing, or preserves. Choose day-neutral strawberries if you want repeated harvests and a longer picking window.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>June-bearing:</strong> one main harvest season, often strong patch production</li>
    <li><strong>Day-neutral:</strong> repeated harvests, useful for fresh picking over time</li>
    <li><strong>Short-season fit:</strong> both can work, but expectations should differ</li>
    <li><strong>Main decision:</strong> big seasonal crop vs longer harvest window</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What June-Bearing Strawberries Are Best For</h2>
  <p>
    June-bearing strawberries are best when you want a strong main crop over a shorter harvest window. They are often used for traditional strawberry patches where the goal is a larger picking period for eating fresh, freezing, baking, or making preserves.
  </p>
  <p>
    The exact timing depends on climate and variety, so the name does not mean they always fruit in June everywhere.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Day-Neutral Strawberries Are Best For</h2>
  <p>
    Day-neutral strawberries are useful when you want fresh berries spread over more of the season. Instead of one main crop, they can produce repeated flushes when conditions are suitable.
  </p>
  <p>
    This can be helpful for small gardens, containers, and gardeners who prefer steady fresh picking rather than one large harvest.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Which Type Is Better for Short Seasons?</h2>
  <p>
    Both types can work in short-season gardens, but they solve different problems. June-bearing types can give a strong crop if the patch is established and winter survival is good. Day-neutral types can be useful where a longer but lighter harvest is preferred.
  </p>
  <p>
    For cold climates, winter hardiness, establishment time, and patch management matter as much as harvest type.
  </p>
</section>

