<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Strawberry Types</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Expecting all varieties to crop the same way:</strong> harvest pattern changes how the patch behaves.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring winter survival:</strong> cold-climate strawberries need to establish and overwinter well.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing only by fruit size:</strong> harvest window and patch vigor matter too.</li>
    <li><strong>Expecting day-neutral plants to act like June-bearers:</strong> their strength is a longer picking window, not always one huge crop.</li>
    <li><strong>Expecting June-bearing plants to produce all season:</strong> they usually focus on a main harvest period.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Best Strategy for Home Gardens</h2>
  <p>
    If you have enough room, grow one reliable June-bearing variety for a main crop and one day-neutral variety for fresh picking over a longer period. In smaller spaces, choose based on whether you want a larger harvest window or a steady snack crop.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>
  <p>
    Strawberry success depends on establishment, winter survival, bloom timing, and summer conditions. Pick the harvest type that matches how you want to use the patch, then check whether the variety fits your local climate.
